# AND Studio — Internal Visualization Platform
## Build specification for Claude Code

> **Addendum (post-build change) — real-only, no mock engine.** At the studio's
> request the shipped app deliberately supersedes §5's *MockProvider* requirement
> and the "runs end-to-end with zero API keys" behavior. The app is now
> **real-only**: image generation requires a Google Gemini key (Nano Banana Pro)
> and presentations require an Anthropic key, both entered by the user in the
> browser. `getActiveProvider()` returns `null` when no key is set and the UI
> prompts the user to add one — there is no mock/demo/placeholder engine. Every
> other part of this spec still applies. (A separate addition: the Concept
> Presentation feature can also generate a self-contained HTML deck via the
> vendored `frontend-slides` skill through Claude.)

> **Addendum 2 — automation + hardening.** Per-feature generation state (input,
> settings, outputs, status) moved from component `useState` into the store
> (`src/store/generation.ts`) so an in-flight run survives a tab switch, can be
> **Cancelled** (AbortSignal threaded to the provider), and a partial batch
> failure keeps images already generated. Three automation pillars were added:
> **scene controls** (`src/lib/scene.ts` + `SceneControls`) that auto-assemble
> the prompt so architects don't write prompts for basics; an **iterative refine
> loop** on any output; and a **cross-feature pipeline** (`sendToFeature`) plus an
> all-faces elevation batch. Hardening: Gemini key moved to the `x-goog-api-key`
> header; the deck preview iframe dropped `allow-same-origin` (it could read the
> stored API keys); a `beforeunload` guard; dialog a11y (`useDialog`); WEBP
> normalized for jsPDF; the presentation stack is lazy-loaded (main chunk
> ~885KB → ~277KB). See README "Scene controls, refine loop & pipeline".

**Read this entire document before writing any code.**

You are building a single-page web application for AND Studio, an architecture practice. Their architects and interior designers will use it to turn sketches and models into renders, elevations, axonometric views, and client concept presentations.

This spec is the source of truth. If something is not specified here, ask before inventing it.

---

## 0. Ground rules

- **Do not invent features.** Four features are specified. Build exactly those four.
- **Do not hardcode any AI provider.** All image generation goes through the adapter interface in §5. A working mock provider is required so the app runs end-to-end with zero API keys.
- **Do not add authentication** in this build. It is a single-studio internal tool. Leave a clear seam for it later (§9).
- **Do not use browser localStorage or sessionStorage** for app state. Use in-memory state plus the storage adapter (§6).
- **Ask before adding any dependency** not listed in §2.
- Build incrementally in the phase order in §10. Do not skip ahead.

---

## 1. What the app does

The studio uploads an input image, picks one of four features, and gets a generated output. Outputs accumulate into a project, and the project can be exported as a client presentation PDF.

The four features chain conceptually — a sketch becomes a render, a render informs an elevation, an elevation becomes an axonometric, and all of them assemble into a presentation — but **each feature must work standalone**.

### Navigation — every tab is always open

**This is a rule, not a preference.** All four features are always accessible from the sidebar. A user clicks any tab, at any time, in any order, and it works.

- **No wizard. No stepper. No linear flow.**
- **No tab is ever locked, greyed out, or disabled** because a previous step wasn't done.
- Feature 03 does not require that feature 02 was run first. The user uploads an elevation directly if they have one.
- Feature 04 (presentation) is reachable at any time. If no images exist yet, show an empty state pointing to the other features — do not disable the tab.
- Each feature accepts its input by direct upload, independent of what else has happened in the session.

The studio's architects will jump straight to whichever tool they need. Treat the four features as four independent instruments that happen to share a project, not as steps in a pipeline.

### The four features

| # | Feature | Input | Output |
|---|---------|-------|--------|
| 01 | Sketch/Plan → Render | A hand sketch or floor plan image | A styled architectural render |
| 02 | Sketch/Model → Elevation | A sketch or SketchUp model screenshot | An elevation design render |
| 03 | Elevation → Axonometric | An elevation image | Axonometric + section-axonometric views, multiple viewpoints |
| 04 | Concept Presentation | Selected outputs from features 01–03 | An arranged presentation, exportable to PDF |

---

## 2. Stack

Use exactly this. Ask before adding anything else.

- **React 18** + **TypeScript** (strict mode on)
- **Vite** as the build tool
- **Tailwind CSS** for styling
- **Zustand** for state management (simple, no boilerplate)
- **react-dropzone** for file uploads
- **jspdf** for PDF export
- **lucide-react** for icons

No component library. Build the UI from scratch per §4 — the visual design is a differentiator for this client and off-the-shelf components will look generic.

