## Addendum · Plan render, architecture styles, output parity, per-tab compare

Client-requested follow-ups after the automation pillars shipped:

1. **Isometric "dollhouse" plan render.** Feature 01 gains an **Isometric dollhouse**
   `style` (`'isometric'`). `buildIsometricPrompt` (`src/lib/prompts.ts`) extrudes a 2D
   plan into a roofless, open-topped 3D volume at a strict 45° isometric angle with
   furniture rendered in 3D and the exact plan layout/openings/proportions preserved —
   the interior-cutaway output architects asked for, distinct from the exterior
   photoreal render. Reuses the same geometry-preservation discipline as the other
   builders.
2. **Architecture styles.** `ARCH_STYLES` (`src/lib/scene.ts`) adds a design-language
   vocabulary — `none` (studio default), contemporary, bauhaus, indian, brutalist,
   minimalist, mediterranean, scandinavian, japanese, artdeco, and `custom` (free
   text). `archStyle` + `customArchStyle` join `SceneOptions`; `archStyleClause`
   mirrors `materialsClause`. The clause is injected into the photoreal and isometric
   render prompts. Surfaced as an **Architecture style** select in `SceneControls`
   (`show.archStyle`), shown for the photoreal and isometric render styles.
3. **Output parity.** A single output renders full-width at the input's size
   (`OutputGrid`/`OutputCard` `size='full'`, `max-h-72`), matching the uploaded plan
   rather than sitting as a small grid cell; two or more keep the compact grid.
4. **Per-tab before/after.** The `ImageCompare` slider (previously Render-only) is now
   on Elevation and Axonometric too, driven by each feature's `inputUsed` snapshot.

Invariants preserved: TS strict, no new deps, no browser persistence of project data,
prompt textarea editable with Reset semantics, provider adapter seam unchanged,
default (studio, golden-hour, no arch style) reproduces the previous photoreal prompt
exactly.

## Addendum · Axonometric — true 3D reconstruction + styles

Reported bug: from a flat elevation the axonometric came back as the same flat,
front-on view (the old prompt said "preserve proportions with no perspective
distortion", so the image model just reproduced the input). Fixes:

1. **Rebuild, don't copy.** `buildAxonometricPrompt` (`src/lib/prompts.ts`) now
   instructs the model to *rebuild the elevation as a 3D massing model*, rotate to a
   three-quarter corner seen from slightly above (front face + returning side wall +
   roof all visible) with genuine depth, and explicitly **not** reproduce a flat
   front-on elevation. The per-image viewpoint (NE/NW/SE/SW) reinforces the corner.
2. **Style options.** `AxonSettings.style` (`realistic` | `lineart` | `bw`) with an
   **Axonometric style** select: realistic 3D render (materials + mood + shadows),
   colour line-art illustration, or pure black-and-white technical linework. Materials/
   mood scene controls show only for `realistic`.
3. **Section decoupled from style.** The section-axonometric cut used to be smuggled
   through `options.style` (`'standard'`/`'section'`); it now travels as its own
   `options.section` boolean (`src/providers/types.ts`), freeing `style` for the real
   axonometric style. Labels updated accordingly (`src/providers/labels.ts`).

## Addendum · Mood Board tab (composed material board)

A new sidebar destination — **Mood Board** (index 05, between Interior and
Presentation) — turns pooled outputs into the client-facing artefact studios hand
over alongside renders. Frontend-only, no generation call, no new dependency.

1. **Canvas renderer.** `src/lib/moodboard.ts` → `renderMoodboard(urls, orientation,
   opts)` composes 1–9 images onto a branded board: a mono ochre eyebrow + serif
   title/subtitle header, an adaptive cover-fit grid (`cols = ceil(sqrt(n))`, cells
   clipped and centre-cropped, partial last row centred), hairline tile frames, and a
   brand-accent tick footer with the project name + studio mark. Portrait 1600×2000 /
   Landscape 2000×1500 / Square 1800×1800; decoded images are cached by URL so the
   live preview re-renders instantly. Returns a PNG dataURL.
2. **Tab UI.** `src/features/moodboard/MoodboardFeature.tsx` — an ordered pool picker
   (max 9, position badges), Board-shape chips, optional title/subtitle, a live
   preview, **Download PNG** (`downloadDataURL`) and **Add to presentation**
   (`addUploads`, lands under *Uploaded*). Empty-state guides users with no images yet.
3. **Wiring.** `TabKey += 'moodboard'` (`src/types/index.ts`), the `FEATURES` map
   (`src/App.tsx`), the sidebar (renumbered Presentation→06, Gallery→07), the hash
   router (`src/lib/useHashRoute.ts` → `#/moodboard`), and a dashboard shortcut.

Invariants preserved: TS strict, no new deps, no browser persistence of project data,
provider adapter seam untouched (the board never calls an image API), the four
generation tabs and their nav indices unchanged (the tab is inserted after Interior).

## Addendum · Reference-chaining (match a reference style)

So a whole set (render → elevation → interior) can share one visual language, any
generation tab can now take a previously generated / uploaded image as a **style
reference**. It reuses the existing second-image seam (`options.referenceImage`)
that the mood-board feature already rides on — no provider change.

1. **State.** `FeatureRun.styleRef: string | null` — the id of a pooled image
   (`src/store/generation.ts`); `removeImage` scrubs it if that image is deleted.
2. **Resolver + picker.** `useStyleRef(feature)` (`src/features/hooks.ts`) resolves
   the id to its dataURL from `poolFromProject`. `StyleRefPicker`
   (`src/components/Scene/StyleRefPicker.tsx`) is a collapsible single-select of the
   pool that reads/writes `styleRef`.
3. **Prompt clauses.** `buildRenderPrompt` gains a `useStyleRef` flag that appends a
   generic "match the reference's palette / materials / mood, keep geometry" clause;
   `buildElevationPrompt` / `buildInteriorPrompt` add a `useStyleRef` branch with
   precedence **own mood board > style reference > design theme** (the mood-board
   wording is left untouched so its test still matches).
4. **Scope + exclusivity.** Wired into **render, elevation, interior** — the three
   restyle-capable tabs. **Axonometric is deliberately excluded**: it is a pure
   geometric conversion that must preserve the input's materials (per the earlier
   "no materials on axonometric" requirement), which a style reference would fight.
   Reference-chaining is mutually exclusive with Compare styles (a fixed reference
   vs. varying the style) and is offered only in a tab's theme mode (a tab's own
   uploaded mood board takes precedence and hides the picker).

Invariants preserved: TS strict, no new deps, provider adapter seam unchanged, the
mood-board flows and their prompts unchanged, no nav change.
